i## How StosVPN Works		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAccording to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hStosVPN's packet processing logic	URL:https://github.com/SideStore/StosVPN/blob/main/TunnelProv/PacketTunnelProvider.swift	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, StosVPN roughly does the following:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Assigns IP address `10.7.0.0` to the iOS device, and configure iOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  to send packets for `10.7.0.0/24` to StosVPN.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Defines an IP address `10.7.0.1` , where StosVPN will simulate a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  computer with iTunes installed.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- For each packet:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - If the packet is sent from `10.7.0.0` to `10.7.0.1` , swap the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    source and destination IP addresses, to send the packet back to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    the iOS device.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis logic is quite simple. SideStore essentially opens some ports		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilocally on the iOS device, simulating a computer with iTunes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iinstalled. Suppose iOS creates a connection like this when trying to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconnect to the simulated computer:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  TCP 10.7.0.0:12345 -> 10.7.0.1:54321		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen WireGuard or StosVPN will swap the source and destination IP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iaddresses (but not the port numbers), rewrite the packet as follows,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand send it back to the iOS device:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  TCP 10.7.0.1:12345 -> 10.7.0.0:54321		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFrom the iOS device's perspective, this is a new TCP connection from `10.7.0.1` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iunrelated to the previous connection sent to the computer. Since the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iport iOS is trying to connect to ( `54321` in this case) should be an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iiTunes port, and SideStore simulates iTunes locally, SideStore should		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibe listening on port `54321` at this time and receiving the data.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter SideStore's simulated iTunes logic processes the data and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
igenerates a reply:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  TCP 10.7.0.0:54321 -> 10.7.0.1:12345		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWireGuard or StosVPN will again swap the source and destination IP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iaddresses:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  TCP 10.7.0.1:54321 -> 10.7.0.0:12345		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis reply packet matches the initial connection sent to the simulated		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomputer. iOS therefore believes it has received a reply from iTunes		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ion the computer, and thus continues updating the developer		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icertificate.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Simulating StosVPN's Working Logic with Nftables		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNow understanding how StosVPN works, we just need to mimic its logic		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iin our own network.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you only have a few iOS devices, and they are all assigned static		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIP addresses, and you have a router running OpenWrt or another Linux		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isystem, you can simply use the following Nftables rules:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  table inet sidestore {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    chain RAW_PREROUTING {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      type filter hook prerouting priority raw; policy accept;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Replace 192.168.0.xxx here with your iOS device's IP address		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      ip saddr 192.168.0.123 ip daddr 10.7.0.1 ip saddr set 10.7.0.1 ip daddr set 192.168.0.123 notrack;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      ip saddr 192.168.0.234 ip daddr 10.7.0.1 ip saddr set 10.7.0.1 ip daddr set 192.168.0.234 notrack;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Add more rules as needed		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe purpose of the above rules is that if a packet is received from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyour iOS device ( `192.168.0.123` or `192.168.0.234` ) destined for `10.7.0.1` (the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivirtual computer), it changes the packet's source IP to `10.7.0.1` (the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivirtual computer) and the destination IP to your iOS device ( `192.168.0.123`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ior `192.168.0.234` ), and then sends it out. The `notrack` here		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idisables connection tracking, which prevents Linux from matching these		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipackets to previously received packets and connection tracking		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ientries, which could make the rules ineffective.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iSince Nftables does not support using packet source/destination IP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iaddresses as variables, it's not possible to achieve the purpose of "swapping		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isource and destination addresses" with a single set of rules.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, we need to add a rule for each iOS device. If you have a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ismall number of iOS devices, you can write a separate rule for each		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idevice's IP address. However, if you have many devices, or if they		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idon't have static IP addresses, you will need to write a rule for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ievery IP address in your home network segment, which can be very		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itroublesome. Also, if your router does not support Nftables or similar		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifirewall functions and cannot rewrite packets in a similar way, you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icannot achieve this functionality.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
